Learning the M0/M1 task with PyCaffe (caffe-segnet flavor)¶

The purpose of this notebook is to explore transfer learning and end-to-end learning on the M0 / M1 tile classification task.

Some weights and caffe .prototxt net definition* provided:
https://github.com/BVLC/caffe/tree/master/models/bvlc_alexnet

*Modified slightly to not use the Input data layer, because my caffe-segnet installation is based on an old commit of caffe-master, which does not include that data layer. Update: I've upgraded the SegNet repo to one based on a newer Caffe Master branch. There is work todo for testing older model compatability with this new installation.

TODO: http://nbviewer.jupyter.org/github/BVLC/caffe/blob/master/examples/net_surgery.ipynb

Inspiration: http://nbviewer.jupyter.org/github/BVLC/caffe/blob/master/examples/00-classification.ipynb

Define several networks trained in different ways, with the same M0 and M1 tiles¶

Architecture Weights Initialized End classifier Training Task Note
AlexNet ImageNet pre-training SoftMax linear classifier ImageNet (1000 classes) BVLC Weights
AlexNet Random initialization SoftMax linear classifier M0/M1 (2 classes) Multiplied data
AlexNet ImageNet pre-training SoftMax linear classifier M0/M1 (2 classes) Multiplied data
GoogLeNet Random initialization SoftMax linear classifier M0/M1 (2 classes) Non-multiplied data

  • M1 has 2046 tiles

Transfer learning network fine-tuned to the M0/M1 task

m0_correct = 0
m1_correct = 0


for m0_img in m0_images:
    img = get_img(m0_img, 227) # Resize each 256 --> 227
    net_transfer, label = infer(net_transfer, img)
    m0_correct+=(label == 0) 
    #print "Image {} classified as \t{}".format(m0_img, label)
    
for m1_img in m1_images:
    img = get_img(m1_img, 227) # Resize each 256 --> 227
    net_transfer, label = infer(net_transfer, img)
    m1_correct+=(label == 1) 
    #print "Image {} classified as \t{}".format(m1_img, label)
    
    
print "Number of M0 images classified as M0: {}".format(m0_correct)
print "Number of M1 images classified as M1: {}".format(m1_correct)

Visualize the filters and net activations¶

Net filters are a visualization of the weights within each convolution layer. The input image is passed through the filter, and the elements of the image which respond to it are allowed to pass through, so to speak. Once training is done, the filters are set.

Filters from ImageNet trained AlexNet

In [16]:
# the parameters are a list of [weights, biases]
filters = net_bvlc.params['conv1'][0].data
vis_square(filters.transpose(0, 2, 3, 1))

# The parameters are fixed once training is finished

(120, 120, 3)

Activation of each filter in response to the input image. Brighter areas mean it responded strongly. In the first layer, we can still see large objects obviously. Going to deeper convolutions, more of the original image impacts each pixel in the activation. Therefore, it quickly becomes difficult or impossible to recognize parts of the original image in deeper convolutions.

ImageNet activation (Convolution 1) to the above image:
